comment.narrative:
1. The Hub has expanded to overall 42 participating countries with Maldives and Benin having joined in 2019, broadened its partnership network signing 4 MOUs with the Bangladesh Public Administration Training Centre, the International Public Management Association for Human Resources (IPMA-HR), the Institute of Public Administration under the president of the Republic of Tajikistan, Civil Service Commission of Maldives and capitalized on its success being viewed as an effective platform for regional cooperation in supporting sustainable development initiatives for the countries in the region and beyond to maximize South-South (East- East), Europe-Asia and triangular cooperation partnerships;
The number of the Hub’s institutional partners reached 55 organizations, including both local and international from different parts of the word, all of which possess a rich knowledge and considerable expertise in public administration and civil service reform;
Successful cooperation has been continued and strong partnership was reinforced with the Hub’s participating countries, international organizations, specialized civil service associations and networks such as the American Society for Public Administration (ASPA), the Asian Association for Public Administration (AAPA), the Network of Institutes and Schools of Public Administration in Central and Eastern Europe (NISPAcee), the Regional School of Public Administration (ReSPA) and the International Management Association for Human Resources (IPMA-HR), International Anti-Corruption Academy (IACA), UNDP Oslo Governance Center, UNDP RBEC, UNDP HDRO, UN ICSC, UNPOG/UNDESA, UN Women, OECD and many others international institutions;
The Hub has established strategic partnership with the Dubai Government being one of the world leaders in the field of governance and public service delivery. This allowed the Hub to organize the Hub’s first conference “Civil Service in the Post-Soviet countries: Challenges, Prospects and Benchmarking” within the World Government Summit 2019 (WGS) platform inviting high level speakers, experts and practitioners engaged in civil service, as well as academia involved in research from 20 countries (Armenia, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Korea, Kyrgyz Republic, FYR Macedonia, Republic of Moldova, Tajikistan, Ukraine, United Arab Emirates, United States of America, Uzbekistan) and international organizations such as OECD and UNDP having well demonstrated and proved the status of the Hub which has become a successful example and internationally recognized model for cooperation and partnership at international ministerial level platforms and forums. As a partner organization, the Hub has been offered and reserved a slot for its sessions within WGS next years.
All activities of the Hub in 2019 were aimed at providing the participating countries with access to the global and regional trends in civil service reforms setting a good example, when one country, such as Kazakhstan, had contributed to achieving the SDGs adopted by the UN General Assembly, particularly Goals 16 and 17; as well as provided its support to other governments in the region to accomplish the SDGs objectives.
2. All activities of the Hub in 2019 were aimed at empowering the civil service institutions of the Hub participating countries via practical leverage on acquired knowledge, training and research skills and expert network drawn from the Hub activities, and benefit from peer-to-peer learning.
Overall, the Hub conducted up to 40 partnership, capacity building, research and knowledge management activities in 2019. In total, around 1455 people (816 men - 56 %, 639 women - 44%) benefitted from the Hub’s partnership, capacity building, research and knowledge management initiatives.
At the substantive and institutional levels, the Hub employed research and knowledge management, capacity building and partnership approaches that were well suited and appropriately customized to ultimately contribute to the establishment of modern, effective and sustainable civil service systems that meet societal expectations for a responsive and transparent civil service delivering public goods and services efficiently in the Hub’s participating countries. The Hub’s participating countries engaged in exchanging and testing contemporary knowledge in order to build their capacity, in generating innovative solutions and practices, and thus contributing to civil service modernization and quality and excellence in public service delivery through following key activities:
- UNDP/HDRO and the Hub, jointly conducted the Regional Experts Group Meeting in Nur-Sultan to discuss the inequality in human development. The discussion was aimed at maximizing stakeholder engagement and ensuring inclusive preparation of HDRs. Prominent economists and experts on inequalities from Albania, Belarus, Croatia, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Serbia, and Turkey took part in the meeting. - Upon the request of the Civil Service Agency of Kazakhstan, such significant activities as factor and point scale (grading) system for civil servants; common framework of competencies (Competencies Model) for civil servants have been developed and introduced to support the reforms in Kazakhstan. Following the initiative of the President Tokayev, the Civil Service Agency of Kazakhstan, the Hub, UNDP in Kazakhstan and the Academy of Public administration have joined efforts and selected 300 candidates (out of 13,212 participated) for the Presidential Personnel Reserve who will have an opportunity to further enhance their knowledge and develop professional skills to potentially be appointed for political and top managerial administrative positions including quasi-public sector entities. The high-quality and transparent selection processes were ensured through automated selection systems and use of advanced HR tools; establishment of professional expert groups to assess applicants for the reserve at number of selection stages. - The Hub initiated a study to develop a country profile on Kazakhstan’s Labour Market Resilience and resent key findings and results according to the methodology algorithm and databases of the Global Labour Resilience Index. The report should give an overview on the labour market of Kazakhstan and its resilience to economic shocks. It should also highlight the structural and policy factors affecting the labour market resilience in order to facilitate expert discussions during the working session in the World Economic Forum in Davos to be held in January 2020. - The “Public sector compensation systems: a comparative review” is currently under elaboration and will be launched in 2020. Preliminary results of the study have been presented and discussed among researchers, experts and civil service practitioners at several the Hub’s events throughout the year 2019. - The 11th and 12th issues of Hub’s International Journal of Civil Service Reform and Practice were published both online and in print versions and have been disseminated among participating countries and partners of the Hub and generated interest from potential authors for the next issue. - “Methodological recommendations for the HR practitioners” was published as a joint knowledge product with the HR Managers Association of Kazakhstan. These guidelines provide a structured method of conducting interviews involving the collection of information on key competencies necessary for work of HR practitioners - Publication of the case study “Communication solutions as a tool to increase public trust in the police: the experience of Georgia” was released in December 2019. - The Hub organized several study visits for high officials of Kazakhstan government including experts and policy makers to learn best practices of public administration in Japan (February 2019, Japan); explor best practices in e-governance, innovation, public service delivery and ICT development from legal, technological, social, and organizational perspectives (May 2019, Korea and Singapore). In partnership with the Civil Service College, Temasek Foundation and the Civil Service Agency of Kazakhstan the Hub co-organized the study visit to Singapore (October 2019) for high official civil servants to explore the best practices in Governance and Public Administration in Singapore. - In partnership with HR Managers Association of Kazakhstan the Hub arranged a series of workshops on interviewing techniques with candidates for public service which gathered together HR managers of central and local government agencies of Kazakhstan. - In partnership with the JSC «ERI» the Hub conducted a workshop on Quality Management in Public Administration and Common Assessment Framework (CAF) which helped better understand the CAF approaches. - The Hub participated in the 5th Annual Meeting of the Effective Institutions Platform at the OECD Headquarters in Paris, on 25-26 April 2019. For its continuous contribution to P2P learning and cooperation with the EIP the Hub representative has been appointed as a member of the EIP Advisory Group for 2 years. - In the framework of Alliance of Practitioners on e-Government Development the Hub hosted 2 workshops: «Current Trends in the e-Government Development» in partnership with the Academy of Public Administration under the President of Republic of Uzbekistan on 30-31 May in Tashkent (Uzbekistan) and «Digital State as The Foundation for Sustainable Development» in partnership with the State Personnel Service of the Kyrgyz Republic on 26-27 August in Bishkek (Kyrgyz Republic). A case study of Azerbaijan published on “Smart Government: Case of Azerbaijan” which was developed by the State Agency for Public Service and Social Innovations under the President of the Republic of Azerbaijan and the Hub. It is planned to develop case studies with other Alliance countries reflecting their experience on the implementation of e-government and its development. Within 2019 Annual Conference the third P2P Alliance was created on “Transformation and Innovations in Governance”. Overall, the third Alliance has comprised 9 practitioners (peers) from Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Ukraine, AAPA, UNDP OGC. - The Hub further contributed to the capacity-building of civil servants of its participating countries, by allocating 2 scholarships for Ukraine and Turkey diplomats to pursue a Master’s degree in the Academy of Public Administration under the President of Kazakhstan. With the Hub’s support, the diplomat of the Brazilian Foreign Ministry benefitted from the training course on “Evidence-Based Decision Making” organized in Nur-Sultan by the Academy of Public Administration under the President of Kazakhstan on 7-9 October 2019. - A joint workshop on “Building Capacities of Training Schools and Institutes of Public Administration to implement the 2030 Agenda and attain the SDGs” was co-organized On 27-29 November 2019 in Almaty by the United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs (UN DESA), United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), the Hub with the support of the Academy of Public Administration under the President of the Republic of Kazakhstan and the “Government for Citizens” Public Corporation” NJSC. The event allowed participants to make recommendations on the next steps needed to strengthen public administration education and the capacity of training schools and institutes of public administration for the implementation of the 2030 Agenda. The participants including senior public service officials, national SDG focal points, as well as institutes of public administration and the public servants from Central Asia and Afghanistan identified specific SDG-related competencies and mindsets from the extended region that are needed for accelerating the implementation of the 2030 Agenda. - The Hub traditionally organized its panel sessions on the platform of the American Society for Public Administration (March 2019), Network of Institutes and Schools of Public Administration in Central and Eastern Europe (May 2019), Astana Economic Forum (May 2019), Nazarbayev University Graduate School of Public Policy (October 2019) inviting heads and representatives of special civil service agencies, international organizations, leading experts and scholars from participating countries to discuss and share the latest developments of civil service policies and best practices in the region. All topics discussed were found participants as relevant, informative and very productive. - Successful cooperation has been continued and strong partnership was reinforced with the Hub’s participating countries and beyond, in particular with Republic of Azerbaijan, Republic of Belarus, Kingdom of Belgium, Canada, Estonia, Georgia, Hungary, Japan, Kyrgyz Republic, the Republic of Korea, Singapore, the United Arab Emirates, Republic of Uzbekistan and Ukraine. The countries have actively participated in activities initiated by the Hub and conducted joint events with the Hub and expressed readiness to enhance collaboration in the area of civil service developments. - On a separate note it is worth mentioning about the Hub’s annual Conference held in June 2019 which gathered around 130 representatives, the heads of civil service agencies from 20 participating countries, the heads and experts from such international organizations as OECD, UNPOG/UNDESA, UN Women, UNDP, UNDP Oslo Governance Center, AAPA, IPMA-HR, EU, World Bank, ReSPA in Nur-Sultan to discuss values, trust and technology in the public sector within the Hub’s Annual Conference. The Conference consisted of several tracks: Hub Talks has been held for the second time this year; the panel session on Gender Equality in Public Administration has been organized jointly with UN Women; Ethics, Integrity and Anticorruption has been another priority focus; - The Hub’s Roster of Experts has been expanded up to 130 experts with more detailed information and currently available for public access via website and countries in the region expressed their interest in using the Hub roster in their work on civil service reform. - The public awareness of the Hub’s major activities was raised by national and international mass and social media through number of media products including press releases, videos, brochure/booklet, visuals and infographics, announcements communicated through the Hub’s website and other social networks.
